For this study, we used an existing registry of patients with an atherosclerotic cardiovascular event (TIA/ischemic stroke, ACS, or PAD) who were referred to our hospital between 2007 and 2009. The database consists of a complete cardiovascular risk profile of 2591 patients with manifest atherosclerotic (n = 1976) disease or elevated cardiovascular risk (n = 615), including relevant biochemical analysis (fasting lipid profile, fasting glucose levels, and GFR calculated by the Cockroft-Gault equation
31
), anthropometry, and complete cardiovascular medical history. Duplex ultrasound evaluation of the carotid arteries was routinely advised in all male patients above the age of 65 years (n = 473; 23.9% of 1976). Because of loss in follow-up (patient returned to previous doctor in other hospital or general practitioner) and for logistic reasons CS evaluation was carried out in 434 (91.8%) of 473 patients. Of these 434 patients, 117 patients were referred with manifest TIA or stroke.
